## Prerequisites

Before running this backend project, install the required backend development tools.

---

## Node.js Installation

Node.js is a JavaScript runtime environment used to execute backend applications outside the browser.

### Step 1: Download Node.js

Download Node.js from the official website:

https://nodejs.org

Install the **LTS (Long Term Support)** version.

### Step 2: Install Node.js

Run the installer and follow the default setup.

Make sure:

- Add to PATH is enabled
- Default installation settings are selected

### Step 3: Verify Installation

Check Node.js version:

```bash
node -v
```

Example:

```bash
v22.x.x
```

Check npm version:

```bash
npm -v
```

Example:

```bash
10.x.x
```

npm is installed automatically with Node.js and is used for package management.

---

## Express.js and Backend Package Installation

Express.js is a backend framework used to build APIs and manage routing.

Initialize Node project if required:

```bash
npm init -y
```

Install Express:

```bash
npm install express
```

Install commonly used backend packages:

```bash
npm install mongoose dotenv cors bcryptjs jsonwebtoken
```

Install nodemon for development:

```bash
npm install nodemon --save-dev
```

Package explanation:

| Package | Purpose |
|----------|---------|
| express | Backend framework |
| mongoose | MongoDB database interaction |
| dotenv | Environment variable configuration |
| cors | Frontend-backend communication |
| bcryptjs | Password hashing |
| jsonwebtoken | JWT authentication |
| nodemon | Auto restart during development |

---

## Installation and Setup

### Clone Repository

```bash
git clone https://github.com/arjunvarikuppala/backend-demo-02.git
```

Move into project folder:

```bash
cd backend-demo-02
```

---

### Install Project Dependencies

```bash
npm install
```

This installs all dependencies listed inside `package.json`.

---

### Configure Environment Variables

Create `.env` file:

```env
PORT=5000
MONGO_URI=your_mongodb_connection
JWT_SECRET=your_secret_key
```

Environment variable explanation:

| Variable | Purpose |
|-----------|---------|
| PORT | Server running port |
| MONGO_URI | MongoDB Atlas connection string |
| JWT_SECRET | JWT secret key |

Example:

```env
PORT=5000
MONGO_URI=mongodb+srv://username:password@cluster.mongodb.net/database
JWT_SECRET=mysecretkey
```

---

## Running Backend Server

Development mode:

```bash
npm run dev
```

Production mode:

```bash
npm start
```

Direct execution:

```bash
node server.js
```

---

## Backend Architecture

The backend follows REST API architecture.

Workflow:

```text
Client Request → Middleware → Router → Controller → Database → Response
```

---

## API Routes and CRUD Operations

The backend uses Express Router and RESTful APIs to perform CRUD operations.

CRUD means:

| Operation | Method | Purpose |
|------------|--------|---------|
| Create | POST | Add new data |
| Read | GET | Retrieve data |
| Update | PUT | Modify existing data |
| Delete | DELETE | Remove data |

---

## Router Structure

Routes are usually organized inside:

```bash
routes/
```

Example:

```bash
routes/
├── authRoutes.js
├── blogRoutes.js
├── userRoutes.js
```

Routes are connected inside `server.js` using:

```js
app.use("/api/auth", authRoutes)
app.use("/api/blogs", blogRoutes)
```

---

## Authentication Routes

Base URL:

```bash
/api/auth
```

| Method | Route | Operation | Description |
|---------|-------|------------|-------------|
| POST | /register | Create | Register new user |
| POST | /login | Read | Login user |
| GET | /profile | Read | Get logged-in user |

Example:

```http
POST /api/auth/register
```

Creates new user account.

Example:

```http
POST /api/auth/login
```

Authenticates user and generates JWT token.

---

## Blog Routes

Base URL:

```bash
/api/blogs
```

| Method | Route | Operation | Description |
|---------|-------|------------|-------------|
| GET | / | Read | Fetch all blogs |
| GET | /:id | Read | Fetch single blog |
| POST | / | Create | Create blog |
| PUT | /:id | Update | Update blog |
| DELETE | /:id | Delete | Delete blog |

Examples:

Fetch blogs:

```http
GET /api/blogs
```

Create blog:

```http
POST /api/blogs
```

Update blog:

```http
PUT /api/blogs/:id
```

Delete blog:

```http
DELETE /api/blogs/:id
```

---

## Middleware

Middleware processes requests before controller execution.

Common middleware:

| Middleware | Purpose |
|------------|---------|
| express.json() | Parse JSON request body |
| cors() | Enable frontend communication |
| dotenv.config() | Load environment variables |
| authMiddleware | Verify JWT token |

Example:

```js
app.use(express.json())
app.use(cors())
```

Protected route example:

```js
router.post("/", authMiddleware, createBlog)
```

---

## Database Configuration

MongoDB Atlas is used for cloud database storage.

Connection example:

```js
mongoose.connect(process.env.MONGO_URI)
```

Successful connection:

```bash
MongoDB Connected
```

---

## API Testing

Backend APIs can be tested using:

- Postman
- Thunder Client
- VS Code REST Client

Example:

```http
GET http://localhost:5000/api/blogs
```

---

## Troubleshooting

If dependencies fail:

```bash
npm install
```

If MongoDB fails:

- Check MONGO_URI
- Verify Atlas username/password
- Allow IP access:

```bash
0.0.0.0/0
```

If server fails:

Check:

- Missing `.env`
- Incorrect scripts
- Package installation issues
- Syntax errors